<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Cameron, Duncan. A sketch of the Customs, Manners, and Way of Living of the Natives, All the Quadrupeds, as Well as Birds, and Fishes, that are Found in the barren Country About Nipigon, <span class="AddHand-editors">[1804]</span>. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0026</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span style="text-decoration:underline;">N</span><sup>o</sup><span style="text-decoration:underline;"> 12</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">even should he be lying on his back doing nothing, and she ever so busy at the time.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The men hunt, build Canoes, which the women sew and pitch; make snow shoe frames ready to net, which the women must finish; Axe helves, Paddles, Sleighs or Trains for hauling in winter, and every other crooked knife work &#8211; but still they undergo a great deal of hardship in winter as well as the women; for very often one man has to hunt and provide for fourteen or fifteen persons.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">There are a great many Cannibals among them; but most of them become so by necessity and starvation &#8211; some have been obliged to eat their children; the husband to eat the wife &#8211; or the wife to eat the husband when she happens to be stronger: &#8211; the weakest is always the first sacrificed to this inhuman Custom, and the strongest, or the most treacherous and cruel, the only Survivor of a numerous family.  There are a few who are Cannibals from inclination,</p>

